			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">Kokichi's E3 Report (Day 2) 
<br />

<br />
Day 2 of E3 was a blast! Not only was I able to play the new Nintendo DS (Duel Screen), which, honestly, will rock the videogame world, but I also got a rare pen to go with it See, the 2nd screen on the Nintendo DS is a touch screen that you use a stylist pen with. I got a rare Nintendo pen that flashes blue when I press a button...I'll take pictures and put them on my favorite forum, EQ2. There are really cool, innovative games that use 2 screens, such as drawing your own Pacman then guiding him to gobble up the ghosts. Think games only need one screen, and that 2 screens is useless? Think again. 
<br />
Anyways, I have lots of new pictures to show. One of the biggest highlights for me was the trailer showing the new Zelda game for the Gamecube that's made to be realistic. You know, basically the exact opposite of Wind Waker...we're talking about looking bad-ass real. The trailer showed Link riding on his horse Epona, attacking monsters while riding, attacking some huge fire boss, defending against arrows, then performing a bad-ass pose. Very, very, VERY cool. 
<br />
I also played Donkey Konga more. I really can't wait for that game to come out...it seems like it'll be a great party game with my friends. Taiko: Drum Master is similar, and I'm fairly good at both, impressing even the people running the booths with my pro Bemani-style game skills. Tahnk yoooooou years of DDRing! Actually, speaking of Dance Dance Revolution, I was playing DDR at one of the booths, and when I finished, some people wanted to interview me. I'm not quite sure what it was for, but they had the special speaker thing and camera and lighting and everything. I think I did a pretty good job for my first interview, heh. They even had me sign a piece of paper saying that they can use what I said on air. Cool, I'm a TV star 
<br />
I also got a few pictures of myself and some more booth babes. Booth babes...honestly, while they're extremely hot (mmmmm...legs...), whenever they talk it's something patronizing and extremely annoying. They keep saying "We're hardcore gamer girls, wooo!", but everyone knows that they're just hired by various companies from a model agency. Hearing them talk personally turns me off...while stupid, hot, bimbo-like girls are attractive and usually a man's dream girl, I really just wish I could have a remote control with a mute button that would work on humans. That and perhaps a "Take of clothes" button... 
<br />

<br />
Okay, now time for what I did at E3 EQ2 related. Well, I got 1 more T-shirt with an EQ2 design, and I plan on getting more tomorrow. That means I currently have 1 T-shirt for raffle or give away or something...*back from 1-2 hour break, sorry for the delay* 
<br />
Okay, now time to list all the stuff I learned today about EQ2 (for some reason the bullet point system thing isn't working on this computer, so bear with me): 
<br />

<br />
(The bad news): There won't be player owned boats at launch. Sorry I related it to not being able to own your own space ships in SWG at launch. Gordon said that it would probably be released in some kind of expansion. 
<br />

<br />
They haven't planned that you will be able to control the boat aka Wind Waker. You would just click on a destination and appear there, with perhaps a short fight with some sea-pirates or something. 
<br />

<br />
Kerrans have Sonic Vision...it makes basically everything black with some yellow outlining that tracks anything moving in yellow outlines. Very cool. 
<br />

<br />
You know that checkered robe that we see so often in pictures? That's, I think, the basic robe...I looted a robe off of a goblin and that's what it looked like when I wore it (I was playing as a kerra today). 
<br />

<br />
More races, such as the kerra, have the "theme" sets for their looks with their piercings and tattoos rather than just choosing "Ring Design 1, 2, 3, etc.". 
<br />

<br />
/moon and /rude are two /emotes they currently have in the game. /moon makes the character stick his rump out (I took a picture of it ), and /rude has the character vigorously "flick off" the target (he does the little chin flip then the arm-up-grab-bicep thing). I asked Gordon if those would be in the final game at launch...he just said "We'll see what we can get away with ". 
<br />

<br />
When Gordon left one of the head designers of the game came and took over his shift (I'm drawing a blank on his name, unfortunately). 
<br />

<br />
Gift of Pathfinder is the name for the speed buff that all Scouts can give. It's a group buff, too. **bleep**, I can't remember the ability you learn afterwards, but, if my memory serves me correctly, it's a spell that makes the enemy's defense weaker. 
<br />

<br />
Arcane Touch is the name of special ability all mages get (it transfers their mana to another person's mana), and some form of a minor healing is the one that priests get. Warriors get the ability to make minor repairs to swords / armor, and Scouts get GoP. 
<br />

<br />
The amount your speed increases with GoP increases as you level up since your skills will get better at them over time. 
<br />

<br />
After talking to either the represenative from Qeynos or Freeport, you talk to the Ambassador and he'll take you off the island. 
<br />

<br />
SOE took out being able to test each "Level-20 Profression" (can't remember what they're called, darnit!), such as Assassins or Barbarians. You'll only be able to test the 4 main ones on the Isle of Refuge. 
<br />

<br />
Once you leave the Isle of Refuge you can never return. 
<br />

<br />
The specifics on the heirloom thing are still undergoing design. They're narrowing it down to either some kind of cool looking object or furniture for your house, or perhaps getting dibs on first names / last names (more likely last names than first names) of your original EQLive characters. 
<br />

<br />
When I asked about shared banking between character accounts, I got a "probably, but it's not definite." 
<br />

<br />
Most of my questions were answered with "Anything can happen" and "We can do anything". Honestly, they can. I think those answers could answer most questions about the game here on these forums. 
<br />

<br />
Harvesting, Skinning, Trapping, Fishing, and Mining were the Artisan skills I can remember that you start out with. They weren't useable, but they were there. 
<br />

<br />
The default icon for anything is a little green goblin. This reminds the Devs that that specific thing needs an icon. 
<br />

<br />
I can't quite remember anything else...when I do, I'll post them, promise.<br />_________________<br /><img src="http://gormsplace.homestead.com/files/gsign.jpg" border="0" /></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
